Let $f:\Bbb{R}^n\to \Bbb{R}$ be a differentiable function such that for some $p>1,$
\begin{align}f(tx)=t^pf(x),\;\forall \;t>0,\;\&\;x\in \Bbb{R}^n \qquad (1)\end{align}
$i.$ I want to show that \begin{align}f'(x)(x)=pf(x),\;\forall \;x\in \Bbb{R}^n \qquad (1)\end{align}
$ii.$ Is the converse also true? I believe that we can take \begin{align}\varphi(t)=f(tx),\;\forall \;t>0\end{align} and show that \begin{align}\frac{d}{dt}\big(\frac{\varphi(t)}{t^p}\big)=0,\end{align} but I don't know how to tranform this to a proof. Any help please?

